Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations have unsettled large parts of Asia.
A year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly grand "state visit plus" to Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-China campaign rhetoric would finally belong to the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the U.S. "strategic engagement" in China with "strategic competition."
To this was added that the U.S., European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is widespread uncertainty in the financial markets, growth is slowing down in China and Europe, and in America, higher interest rates are beginning to take effect.
The uncertainty regarding the future development of nuclear negotiations with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What, then, are the prospects for U.S.-China relations in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on reducing the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make in this regard will be reached by March.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If tariffs were negotiated one by one, it could take a year.
Should Chinese economic reformers, however, adopt a more drastic approach by gradually committing to the abolition of all tariffs and urging Americans to do the same, a faster result could be in sight.
That would, however, go against the grain of Chinese trade officials, who have been trained for decades to be stingy, let alone give everything at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Nonetheless, a reform is something different from the way contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there were no specific provisions on technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under President Barack Obama's administration could be reaffirmed.
Their enforcement or legal action against violations of intellectual property rights remains, however, a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism involves subjecting relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international commercial arbitration institutions based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing the protection of intellectual property.
Should China raise objections, it could develop its own international commercial arbitration process based in China.
For that, however, it would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel in order to strengthen its international credibility.
No one has trust in Chinese trade courts.
For its own domestic reform needs, China must move toward completely independent trade and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the penal chamber continues to be subject to political control.
The American concerns regarding state subsidies within the framework of the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will be difficult to resolve.
The fact is that all countries provide a certain level of state support to their domestic technology industries, even though this support is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, the enforcement would be difficult to assess.
I am not confident that a negotiation result will be achieved in this area.
Perhaps America simply needs to outcompete China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not exclude the possibility that China offers tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
So China might decide over time to take the drastic step of agreeing to duty-free trade not only with the U.S., but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would have an almost irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to counter the trend towards protectionism.
In the course of such a shift, China could request the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to join, in order to surpass the U.S. (which withdrew from the free trade agreement as one of Trump's first official actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably nimble when it discovers a political opening and market access.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the U.S., China is likely to be striving in 2019 in its general foreign and security policy to reduce conflicts in its relations with other countries.
There is already a certain normalization in relations with Japan.
Recent data from the Japanese coast guard indicate a significant decrease in Chinese incursions into the area of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also aims to reduce tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea by accelerating negotiations on a "Code of Conduct."
Moreover, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, given the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports independence, led by Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would, of course, change radically if the U.S. continues with further major arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the U.S. in the South China Sea continue to occur, and the conflict could escalate if the U.S. more forcefully emphasizes its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Across all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project, the "New Silk Road."
In recent months, however, the initiative in China has caused less political controversy.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns regarding the long-term financiability of the New Silk Road.
In 2019, therefore, triumphant news about the New Silk Road could be heard less frequently.
Furthermore, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It is likely to continue appearing as a new advocate of the WHO and to maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More measured representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on existing mechanisms of the global rules-based system, especially if the U.S. consistently shows contempt for them.
While China attempts to stabilize its relations with the U.S. and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership is likely to use the year 2019 to form a well-founded judgment about the future of U.S. policy: The consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new U.S. strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that America's stance toward China has undergone a fundamental change, they are still uncertain about the exact form this change takes and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
